22:42.862 --> 22:44.862
and a little bit of time
to do it in.

22:44.906 --> 22:46.906
<i> - I have to keep doing it.</i>
<i> I'm not gonna give up.</i>

22:46.949 --> 22:49.075
I've got to get this done.

22:49.118 --> 22:51.118
- Work more fastlier.
- Yeah, fastlier.

22:51.162 --> 22:52.495
- Come on, come on, come on.

22:52.538 --> 22:54.163
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:54.207 --> 22:56.624
- This is getting down to it.

22:56.667 --> 23:00.002
- Ten, nine, eight,

23:00.046 --> 23:03.130
seven, six, five,

23:03.174 --> 23:06.884
four, three, two, one.

23:06.928 --> 23:08.928
Drop your tools,
stop your work.

23:08.971 --> 23:12.181
Please return to your anvils
with your blades, thank you.

23:12.225 --> 23:14.016
<i> - So time's up.</i>
<i> It's over.</i>

23:14.060 --> 23:18.771
[groans]
I have a knife...maybe.

23:18.815 --> 23:21.023
<i> - A bladesmith is probably</i>
<i> his worst critic,</i>

23:21.067 --> 23:22.817
<i> but given the time,</i>

23:22.860 --> 23:26.987
I am satisfied with the job
I could do.

23:27.031 --> 23:29.990
- Bladesmiths,
this is the strength test.

23:30.034 --> 23:31.367
I'm going to be testing
the strength

23:31.411 --> 23:33.160
and durability
of your blades

23:33.204 --> 23:35.663
by chopping into
these boots.

23:35.706 --> 23:38.749
If the knives can cut through
the leather without damage,

23:38.793 --> 23:41.335
it shows how strong
the edge is.

23:41.379 --> 23:42.711
David, are you ready?

23:42.755 --> 23:44.171
- Tear it up.
- All right.

23:44.215 --> 23:46.340
- This is gonna be so cool.

23:46.384 --> 23:49.176
<i> I'm really curious to see</i>
<i>what my blade does to the boot.</i>

23:49.220 --> 23:51.762
They are going to be trying
to cut the toe off.

23:51.806 --> 23:55.349
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

23:55.393 --> 23:57.560
<i> I can't see anything.</i>

23:57.603 --> 23:59.687
It made
a very satisfying whack,

23:59.730 --> 24:01.522
<i> but it didn't cut</i>
<i> the boot.</i>

24:01.566 --> 24:03.524
At least the blade
didn't break.

24:03.568 --> 24:05.234
- David, one thing I like
about your knife,

24:05.278 --> 24:07.611
it's very light and fast.

24:07.655 --> 24:09.363
Kinda makes me want
to chop through the jungle,

24:09.407 --> 24:12.324
but on the boot,
you didn't do bad.

24:12.368 --> 24:13.993
I don't see
any edge damage.

24:14.036 --> 24:16.245
I don't have any wrinkles
or fold-overs.

24:16.289 --> 24:17.997
Overall, good job.
- Awesome, thank you.

24:18.040 --> 24:19.582
- Jason, you ready?
- Yes, sir.

24:19.625 --> 24:22.418
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

24:22.462 --> 24:29.300
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

24:29.343 --> 24:30.926
<i> - A little bit disappointed</i>
<i> on the inside.</i>

24:30.970 --> 24:32.636
Barely nicked it.

24:32.680 --> 24:36.474
- Well, Jason, your knife handle
is very blocky to me.

24:36.517 --> 24:41.145
It's hard to manage it and also
focus on hitting something.

24:41.189 --> 24:42.730
Overall, it held up.
- Thank you, sir.

24:42.773 --> 24:45.149
- Got a little bit of a cut
in the boot.

24:45.193 --> 24:46.525
Well done.
- Thank you.

24:46.569 --> 24:47.943
- Todd, you ready?

24:47.987 --> 24:49.862
- Do it.
- Do it.

24:49.906 --> 24:52.823
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

24:52.867 --> 24:59.830
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

24:59.874 --> 25:02.208
- Nice.
Wow.

25:02.251 --> 25:04.627
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

25:04.670 --> 25:06.754
- Todd, I notice your knife
has developed

25:06.797 --> 25:10.007
a very interesting patina.

25:10.051 --> 25:12.801
- As well as my hand.
[laughter]

25:12.845 --> 25:14.887
- I was a little concerned
because your tang was very...

25:14.931 --> 25:17.181
- Yeah, yeah.
- Small there so,

25:17.225 --> 25:19.975
but I liked that you pulled off
the D-guard.

25:20.019 --> 25:21.977
- Thank you.
- Overall, I'm impressed.

25:22.021 --> 25:23.479
You put a ferrule on it.

25:23.523 --> 25:24.855
It looks like something
that came right off

25:24.899 --> 25:26.649
of a pirate ship to me.
You did good.

25:26.692 --> 25:27.858
- Thank you. Thank you.

25:27.902 --> 25:29.401
- Next up
is the sharpness test.

25:29.445 --> 25:31.320
Doug?

25:31.364 --> 25:33.656
- Bladesmiths, to see how sharp
the edge of your blade is,

25:33.699 --> 25:35.449
I will take your weapon

25:35.493 --> 25:37.409
and will attempt to cut through
these fire hoses.

25:37.453 --> 25:39.411
Let's see how well
your blades perform.

25:39.455 --> 25:40.996
Dave, you're up first.
Are you ready?

25:41.040 --> 25:43.541
- Absolutely.
- Let's do this.

25:43.584 --> 25:45.626
<i> - I am so nervous right now.</i>

25:45.670 --> 25:48.045
Fire hose is made to be
abrasion resistant,

25:48.089 --> 25:50.464
so it may just turn the blade,
for all I know.

25:50.508 --> 25:52.633
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

25:52.677 --> 25:54.134
[bleep].

25:59.392 --> 26:00.849
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

26:00.893 --> 26:03.018
<i> - I am so nervous right now.</i>

26:03.062 --> 26:05.479
Fire hose is made to be
abrasion resistant,

26:05.523 --> 26:09.024
<i> so it may just turn the blade,</i>
<i> for all I know.</i>

26:09.068 --> 26:10.651
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

26:12.780 --> 26:16.365
[bleep].

26:16.409 --> 26:18.826
- Well, Dave, you've got a belly
on your blade,

26:18.869 --> 26:21.120
enough to want to pull in
and slice,

26:21.163 --> 26:23.247
but still running
across the edge

26:23.291 --> 26:25.374
was not sharp enough
to cut all the way through.

26:25.418 --> 26:27.626
But it did lacerate
the hose.

26:27.670 --> 26:30.754
The handle construction--
a little bit long,

26:30.798 --> 26:32.548
but, you know,
it is comfortable.

26:32.592 --> 26:34.008
Jason, you're next.
You ready?

26:34.051 --> 26:35.843
- I'm ready.

26:35.886 --> 26:38.721
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

26:38.764 --> 26:42.182
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

26:42.226 --> 26:43.392
- Good job.
- Thanks.

26:43.436 --> 26:44.852
- Really good job.

26:44.895 --> 26:46.562
- Jason, you have
a very sharp knife,

26:46.606 --> 26:48.564
and it almost cut
all the way through.

26:48.608 --> 26:50.816
The handle--
I like the flaring there.

26:50.860 --> 26:53.319
That prevents it from wanting
to slip out of it,

26:53.362 --> 26:55.446
but it is
a little blocky.

26:55.489 --> 26:59.033
Overall, it will cut.
- Thank you.

26:59.076 --> 27:00.743
- Good job.
Todd, you're up next.

27:00.786 --> 27:02.369
You ready?
- Ready to go.

27:02.413 --> 27:03.787
- Let's do this.

27:03.831 --> 27:06.790
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

27:06.834 --> 27:13.714
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:15.134 --> 27:17.760
[laughter]

27:17.803 --> 27:19.970
First off, Todd, let's talk
about your D-guard

27:20.014 --> 27:21.639
and your handle construction
here.

27:21.682 --> 27:23.015
It feels good.

27:23.059 --> 27:25.225
With a D-guard,
you almost feel like

27:25.269 --> 27:27.227
close-quarter fighting,
just punch with it,

27:27.271 --> 27:28.729
because it's so close
to the hand

27:28.773 --> 27:30.314
and a shorter blade.

27:30.358 --> 27:31.982
Your blade is sharp enough

27:32.026 --> 27:34.610
to lacerate all the way
through the back of the hose.

27:34.654 --> 27:36.403
It didn't cut
all the way through,

27:36.447 --> 27:38.697
but nonetheless,
this, sir, will cut.

27:38.741 --> 27:41.533
Good job.
- Thank you.

27:41.577 --> 27:44.620
- The judges have discussed
the details of your blades,

27:44.664 --> 27:46.997
and it's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

27:47.041 --> 27:50.959
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

27:51.003 --> 27:54.088
Jason, your blade
did not make the cut.

27:54.131 --> 27:55.964
- Jason, I really appreciate
what you did

27:56.008 --> 27:57.591
with the inlay
in your handle,

27:57.635 --> 28:00.010
<i> but that inlay didn't really</i>
<i> allow you</i>

28:00.054 --> 28:02.388
<i> to contour that handle much,</i>
<i> and it wound up being blocky.</i>

28:02.431 --> 28:04.848
<i> Between that and that crack</i>
<i> at the tip of the blade,</i>

28:04.892 --> 28:07.017
<i> which is getting larger,</i>

28:07.061 --> 28:08.644
well, those two things
are the reasons

28:08.688 --> 28:10.979
we're letting you go.

28:11.023 --> 28:15.192
- Jason, please surrender
your weapon.

28:15.236 --> 28:17.569
<i> - I would have liked</i>
<i> to have moved on.</i>

28:17.613 --> 28:19.488
I look back now,
and I probably should have

28:19.532 --> 28:21.448
<i> done things a little bit</i>
<i> different.</i>

28:21.492 --> 28:23.283
I did the best I can.

28:23.327 --> 28:25.828
<i> I miss my wife,</i>
<i> I'm ready to get home to her.</i>

28:25.871 --> 28:28.455
Maybe jump on the motorcycle,
go for a ride.

28:28.499 --> 28:31.333
It was a great experience.
It's one I'll never forget.

28:31.377 --> 28:35.504
<i> And I appreciate</i>
<i> the opportunity.</i>

28:35.548 --> 28:37.881
- David, Todd,
congratulations.

28:37.925 --> 28:39.341
Your work has advanced you

28:39.385 --> 28:41.885
into this final round
of competition.

28:41.929 --> 28:44.304
Now we're sending you
back to your home forges

28:44.348 --> 28:46.890
to re-create an iconic blade
from history.

28:46.934 --> 28:48.600
That weapon is...

28:48.644 --> 28:50.310
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

28:50.354 --> 28:51.770
The cavalry saber.

28:51.814 --> 28:55.232
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:55.276 --> 28:58.610
<i> The cavalry saber emerged in</i>
<i>Europe around the 18th century.</i>

28:58.654 --> 29:01.155
<i> With new developments</i>
<i> in battlefield tactics,</i>

29:01.198 --> 29:02.740
<i> cavalry soldiers</i>
<i> didn't have time</i>

29:02.783 --> 29:04.616
<i> for fancy swordplay</i>
<i> or thrusts.</i>

29:04.660 --> 29:06.994
<i> The cavalry saber allowed</i>
<i> mounted soldiers</i>

29:07.037 --> 29:09.288
<i> to attack with a deadly</i>
<i> overhand slash.</i>

29:09.331 --> 29:10.914
<i> It wasn't just the curve</i>
<i> of the weapon</i>

29:10.958 --> 29:12.708
<i> that made it</i>
<i> a dangerous chopper.</i>

29:12.752 --> 29:14.418
<i> The tip of the blade</i>
<i> was thicker than the hilt,</i>

29:14.462 --> 29:16.336
<i> adding more power</i>
<i> to the swing.</i>

29:16.380 --> 29:18.505
<i> The sword has become one</i>
<i> of the more iconic weapons</i>

29:18.549 --> 29:20.924
<i> of its time and was used by</i>
<i> Captain Jack Aubrey</i>

29:20.968 --> 29:22.926
<i> in the film</i>
<i> "Master and Commander."</i>

29:22.970 --> 29:25.679
<i>Though lethal enough to cut off</i>
<i> an arm with a single swing,</i>

29:25.723 --> 29:27.765
<i> the advent of gunpowder</i>
<i> saw the cavalry saber</i>

29:27.808 --> 29:30.726
<i> relegated to</i>
<i> ceremonial purposes.</i>

29:30.770 --> 29:32.186
<i> - That's right up my alley.</i>

29:32.229 --> 29:33.645
As soon as he pulled
the sheet off,

29:33.689 --> 29:35.481
I knew what
I was gonna make already.

29:35.524 --> 29:37.316
- You'll have five days
at your home forge

29:37.359 --> 29:38.859
to complete this project,

29:38.903 --> 29:40.944
so show us something
unique

29:40.988 --> 29:42.863
that only you could make.

29:42.907 --> 29:44.656
- Well, I tell you,
if I can make a kukri

29:44.700 --> 29:46.742
out of a gun barrel,

29:46.786 --> 29:49.912
then making a saber
shouldn't be a big problem.

29:49.955 --> 29:51.497
- You must include
a 2- to 3-inch

29:51.540 --> 29:52.998
curve in the blade

29:53.042 --> 29:57.085
and a D or stirrup guard
over the handle.

29:57.129 --> 29:59.379
At the end of those five days,
you will return

29:59.423 --> 30:01.715
and present your sabers
to our panel of judges.

30:01.759 --> 30:03.550
Only after they've put
your weapons

30:03.594 --> 30:05.594
through a series
of rigorous tests,

30:05.638 --> 30:08.055
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion.

30:08.098 --> 30:11.141
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

30:11.185 --> 30:13.977
- Yeah.
- Let's do this.

30:14.021 --> 30:18.482
<i> [upbeat music]</i>

30:18.526 --> 30:20.818
<i> - I'm back at my forge,</i>
<i> happy to be home.</i>

30:20.861 --> 30:23.153
My design will actually be
off an original.

30:23.197 --> 30:25.489
<i> The blade will have</i>
<i> a fair amount of curvature.</i>

30:25.533 --> 30:27.324
<i> It'll be beautiful</i>
<i> and functional.</i>

30:27.368 --> 30:30.619
I used coal my whole life.
That's how I started out.

30:30.663 --> 30:33.038
Everybody complains
about coal.

30:33.082 --> 30:35.249
"Oh, it's hard.
Oh, I can't keep the fire hot."

30:35.292 --> 30:36.667
They just don't know
what they're doing.

30:36.710 --> 30:39.586
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:39.630 --> 30:41.296
Now here's where
you gotta watch.

30:41.340 --> 30:43.966
You don't want to overheat--
whoop--your metal.

30:44.009 --> 30:45.968
<i> I make my blades</i>
<i> the old way.</i>

30:46.011 --> 30:48.512
I forge them by hand.
I use all hand tools.

30:48.556 --> 30:50.264
<i> It takes me</i>
<i> a little bit longer,</i>

30:50.307 --> 30:53.016
but it shows
in the finished product.

30:53.060 --> 30:55.227
It's not really cheap;
it's learning how to do things,

30:55.271 --> 30:57.187
and I'm a kind of guy
that wouldn't pay a penny

30:57.231 --> 31:00.899
to see a pissant eat a bale
of hay on Sunday.

31:00.943 --> 31:03.110
So I can fabricate
just about anything.

31:03.153 --> 31:07.239
I can do custom cars,
bikes, rehab houses.

31:07.283 --> 31:10.534
So, they're wanting a sword,
they're gonna get a sword.

31:10.578 --> 31:11.869
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

31:11.912 --> 31:15.247
<i> [upbeat music]</i>

31:15.291 --> 31:17.291
- And away we go.

31:17.334 --> 31:19.459
<i> We're here in Oklahoma City</i>
<i> in my home shop.</i>

31:19.503 --> 31:21.044
Behold the mess.

31:21.088 --> 31:23.046
My shop is just
very bare bones.

31:23.090 --> 31:28.093
I've got hammers, fire,
and a grinder.

31:28.137 --> 31:30.053
No turning back now.

31:30.097 --> 31:34.016
My experience with swords
is mostly fantasy blades,

31:34.059 --> 31:36.685
like katanas, a pirate cutlass,
that sort of thing,

31:36.729 --> 31:39.229
<i> so I've never tried</i>
<i> to forge a blade that large</i>

31:39.273 --> 31:41.481
<i> and never all in</i>
<i> one forging session.</i>

31:41.525 --> 31:45.402
This is where that power hammer
would come in real handy.

31:45.446 --> 31:49.031
Every heat, it's inducing a
little curve or a little twist.

31:49.074 --> 31:50.866
<i> It's just such a long blade.</i>

31:50.910 --> 31:53.410
<i> I correct one little warp</i>
<i> or one little bend,</i>

31:53.454 --> 31:55.370
<i> there's another one beside it</i>
<i> that gets a little worse.</i>

31:55.414 --> 31:56.955
[groans]

31:56.999 --> 31:58.624
<i> I'm heating,</i>
<i> I'm hammering.</i>

31:58.667 --> 32:00.292
<i> I'm heating, I'm hammering</i>

32:00.336 --> 32:04.421
<i> and hammering</i>
<i> and hammering.</i>

32:04.465 --> 32:07.299
This thing is a monster
of a blade.

32:07.343 --> 32:08.592
[exhales deeply]

32:08.636 --> 32:13.013
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:13.057 --> 32:14.848
<i> - Day two,</i>
<i> and I'm feeling good.</i>

32:14.892 --> 32:17.351
<i> I really want to make</i>
<i> this blade superb,</i>

32:17.394 --> 32:19.561
<i> so I pound the edge in.</i>

32:19.605 --> 32:22.105
<i> Takes me a little bit longer,</i>
<i> but it's worth the time.</i>

32:22.149 --> 32:23.565
See that edge on that?

32:23.609 --> 32:26.401
I'm basically
right down to sharp.

32:26.445 --> 32:30.072
Best-case scenario is, tomorrow
I get this blade quenched

32:30.115 --> 32:31.740
and start on the guard
and the handles,

32:31.784 --> 32:33.158
and see what I got.

32:33.202 --> 32:35.160
[blows]
Uh-oh.

32:35.204 --> 32:37.829
[bleep].
I just burned it out.

32:37.873 --> 32:40.540
The thing with coal
is, one crank too many,

32:40.584 --> 32:42.459
<i> it just crumbles.</i>
<i> The blade is junk.</i>

32:42.503 --> 32:44.711
The could be
just the ruination right there.

32:49.426 --> 32:51.760
<i> [dramatic music]</i>

32:51.804 --> 32:54.471
<i> - I'm cranking the forge,</i>
<i> I pull the blade out...</i>

32:54.515 --> 32:55.681
[blows]
Uh-oh.

32:55.724 --> 32:58.433
<i> And I see the burnout.</i>

32:58.477 --> 33:00.435
[bleep].

33:00.479 --> 33:03.438
The thing with coal
is, you cannot see the color,

33:03.482 --> 33:05.148
<i> and you're trying to guess</i>
<i> what the heat is.</i>

33:05.192 --> 33:07.401
<i> And just a half a crank</i>
<i> could burn it up.</i>

33:07.444 --> 33:10.445
The blade is junk.
Um...

33:10.489 --> 33:12.864
[bleep].

33:12.908 --> 33:14.992
I'm kinda PO'ed.

33:15.035 --> 33:18.829
<i> I just spent almost two days</i>
<i> making this blade,</i>

33:18.872 --> 33:21.540
<i> but when the going</i>
<i> gets tough,</i>

33:21.583 --> 33:24.459
<i> the tough get going.</i>

33:24.503 --> 33:25.836
I'm gonna start another blade.

33:25.879 --> 33:29.006
<i> [upbeat music]</i>

33:29.049 --> 33:31.717
<i> - Finally, I'm done</i>
<i> with all the rough forging.</i>

33:31.760 --> 33:34.177
<i> About ready to heat-treat.</i>

33:34.221 --> 33:36.680
This sword is a beast,
it really is.

33:36.724 --> 33:39.349
<i> If this quench goes poorly</i>
<i> and I have to start over,</i>

33:39.393 --> 33:41.435
it really could jeopardize
my ability

33:41.478 --> 33:43.270
to turn in a finished blade.

33:43.313 --> 33:45.022
Hold on to your butts.

33:45.065 --> 33:48.775
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

33:50.029 --> 33:52.988
<i> [suspenseful music]</i>

33:53.032 --> 33:54.948
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

33:54.992 --> 33:56.825
This baby's hard
like trigonometry.

33:56.869 --> 33:58.910
Look at it.
Spring!

33:58.954 --> 34:01.288
I'm gonna go ahead and take some
of these warps out with a torch

34:01.331 --> 34:04.207
and move on to grinding.

34:04.251 --> 34:05.667
[pings]

34:05.711 --> 34:07.335
[bleep].

34:07.379 --> 34:09.212
Every bladesmith
knows this sound.

34:09.256 --> 34:11.798
It's the dreaded ping
of death.

34:11.842 --> 34:14.009
Man, I really don't like
that sound.

34:14.053 --> 34:15.802
I forgot that when you
dip it in water,

34:15.846 --> 34:18.638
<i> built a bunch of stress...</i>

34:18.682 --> 34:21.475
[pings]
Son of a bitch.

34:21.518 --> 34:23.560
Caused it to crack.

34:23.604 --> 34:25.395
<i> Can't even explain how</i>
<i> disappointed I am right now.</i>

34:25.439 --> 34:27.230
<i> Half the time is gone,</i>

